      "strongs_list": "[{\"strong\": \"H4906\", \"count\": 1}, {\"strong\": \"G1761\", \"count\": 1}]",
      "description": "Imagination is the inner capacity to form mental images of what is not immediately present — to picture, conceive, and give form to what does not yet exist or what cannot be directly seen. The Hebrew vocabulary here covers figures and reflections; the Greek covers reflection and contemplation. In Scripture imagination is treated with some suspicion when it runs unchecked (the imaginations of the heart are evil continually, Genesis 6) but it is also foundational to prayer, prophecy, and the capacity to hope for what is not yet seen.",
      "origin": "original_list",
      "source_category": null,
      "inference_note": "Imagination as a faculty of the mind — the capacity to form mental images and conceive possibilities — is ABSENT as a direct biblical term. Scripture addresses imagination primarily in the context of corrupt mental fabrications rather than as a neutral creative faculty.",
      "anchor_verses": " Gen 6:5; 2 Cor 10:5",
      "session_b_status": null,
